at ClassLoader.loadClass functions correctly in native environments. It seems that for ClassLoader.loadClass to work, the class must be reachable. I could reference a class, like X509CertParser, in a test to assert its presence, which should make it reachable. But I’m also considering that using newInstance via reflection might still require reflection metadata for the constructor. There’s a lot to consider here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering public API implications**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the public provider SPI class, focusing only on the active class. It could serve as a constant for ensuring native includes. However, the test doesn’t seem to confirm the dynamic path through the class, which is okay for setup. The public API is still X509StreamParser, and I wonder if I could reference the no-argument constructor through a Supplier. I’m considering adding a static field for the X509CertParser class to make things more accessible. I’ll also explore the reflection aspect for instantiation.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting test coverage**\\n\\nI’m considering whether to provide metadata if tests reach the JVM. It seems like a previous workflow might have failed before the coverage report due to issues with the dynamically loaded class, X509CertParser, which is missing metadata. If there’s no debug info, the coverage might be unhelpful. I wonder if dynamic-access coverage is based on bytecode coverage from JaCoCo. I’ll need to look into the JaCoCo execution report for more insights.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_AuWUaAvlxcuoOnfjVZK0yhK7|fc_0f3e3f7c69a63527016a25a67b5844819085719479b789a154", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcprov-jdk15on/1.48/build/reports/jacoco -type f | sort | head -80 && rg \"X509Util\" tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcprov-jdk15on/1.48/build/reports/jacoco -n || true", "timeout": 10}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"find tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcpr